# Tailwind Mobile-First Styling

## Mobile-First Approach

- Design for 375px base width FIRST, then scale up with responsive prefixes.
- Base styles (no prefix) = mobile. Add `sm:`, `md:`, `lg:` for larger screens.

```tsx
// GOOD - mobile-first
<div className="px-4 py-2 sm:px-6 md:px-8 lg:px-12">

// BAD - desktop-first, hiding on mobile
<div className="hidden md:block">
```

## No Inline Styles

- Use Tailwind utility classes exclusively.
- Do NOT use `style={{ }}` props.
- For dynamic values (e.g., timer progress), use CSS custom properties set via `style` only as a last resort and document why.

## Touch Targets

- All interactive elements must have a minimum touch target of 44x44px.
- Use `min-h-11 min-w-11` (44px) on buttons and tappable areas.
- Add adequate spacing between adjacent tap targets.

```tsx
// GOOD - accessible touch target
<button className="min-h-11 min-w-11 px-4 py-3 text-base">

// BAD - too small for fingers
<button className="px-1 py-0.5 text-xs">
```

## Spacing and Layout

- Use `flex` and `grid` for layouts, not floats or positioning hacks.
- Use consistent spacing scale: `gap-2`, `gap-3`, `gap-4` for component gaps.
- Add `safe-area-inset` padding on bottom for devices with home indicators:
  `pb-safe` or `pb-[env(safe-area-inset-bottom)]`.

## Typography

- Base font size is `text-base` (16px) for readability on mobile.
- Do not go below `text-sm` (14px) for any user-facing text.
- Use `font-medium` or `font-semibold` for emphasis, not color alone.
